The paper discusses the use of agent-based modeling and simulation tools for complex networks, which falls under the category of multi-agent systems (cs.MA). The specific focus on peer-to-peer systems and ad hoc networks suggests a possible fit with the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) category. The mention of human/animal/habitat interaction suggests a possible fit with social and information networks (cs.SI) or distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) categories. Finally, the use of NetLogo, a tool commonly used in social simulation, suggests a possible fit with the cybernetics (cs.CY) category.
